          "body": "The chapter pivots at 1:27 with *monon* — *only*. One thing matters: that the Philippians conduct themselves (*politeuesthe* — live as citizens) in a manner worthy of the gospel. Paul deliberately reaches for citizenship vocabulary because Philippi prides itself on Roman citizenship. Your true commonwealth is the gospel; live accordingly. The marks: standing firm in one spirit, striving together with one mind for the faith of the gospel (1:27), unalarmed by opponents (1:28). And then the chapter's most counterintuitive claim: it has been *graciously granted* (*charizomai* — given as a gift of grace) to the Philippians not only to *believe* but also to *suffer* for Christ's sake (1:29). Suffering is not a glitch in the Christian life; it is part of the package, given on the same terms as faith itself."
